a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.3df2564b-c203-445a-8877-cfade2f86669.description=
The operation "List Flow Run History" retrieves a list of runs for a given flow, using the REST API.

Inputs\:
    host - The host running the Central service. The host can also be given as a url.
Default value\: localhost.
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default\: 8080.
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http.
Valid values\: http, https.
    trustKeystore - The path of the truststore file. It may be empty if HTTPS server authentication is not to be used.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false.
    trustPassword - Password to unlock the truststore. Provide this input only if trustKeystore is not empty.
    flow - The uuid or the path of the flow. If given by path an extra call will be made (using get /flows/tree/level) to translate it to uuid. Leading and trailing slashes will be stripped.
Example\: Library/Utility Operations/Display Message
Example\: 434e6fa2-26bc-4e84-9e1f-0aa6946cf920
    startTime - The start time used to filter out all executions that started after this date. This time input field accepts multiple syntaxes, including GMT format or Unix Epoch timestamp.  If it is left empty, no start time filtering will be applied.
Example 1\: Sat, 12 Aug 1995 13\:30\:00 GMT
Example 2\: Sat, 12 Aug 1995 13\:30\:00 GMT+0430 (4 hours, 30 minutes west of the Greenwich meridian)
Example 3\: May 29 2013 6\:00 PM
Example 4\: 1437565444098
    endTime - The end time used to filter out all executions that ended before this date. This input field has the same format as "startTime". If it is left empty, no end time filtering will be applied.

Results\:
    runCount - Represents the number of flow runs returned by the operation.
    returnResult - A JSON array representation of the flow runs. Each item of the array has the following properties\: 
    runId -  The runId of the flow run.
    status - The status of the flow run.
    startTime - The start time of the flow run since 1/1/1970 00\:00am, in milliseconds.
    duration - The time the run took to finish in milliseconds. This is missing if the flow is not completed.
    numSteps - The number of steps. This is missing if "light" input is set to true.
    userId - The name of the user account who started the run.

Responses\:
    success -The operation retrieved the status of the running flow.
    failure - Could not connect to central web service. Invalid flow.
	
Notes\:
1) If you use startTime and endTime you will get the executions that started and ended in that interval so that startTime < executionStartTime < executionEndTime < endTime.
2) Only executions started before current local time will be retreived.
3) Use the operations and flows from Library/Utility Operations/Containers/JSON to parse the returnResult.
4) Use the utility operations from "Date and Time" folder to pass valid values for "startTime" and "endTime" input fields.
5) Unix Epoch timestamp represents the number of milliseconds that have elapsed since 1 January 1970.
6) You may add these extra inputs\:
    authType - The type of authentication used to send the request to the Central service.
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the Central host.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyusername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used.
Example\: %JAVA_HOME%/jre/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file.
    lastNFlows - Only these last n flows will be searched and listed. Defaults to 1000 if left empty.
Example\: 1000
    light - If true the execution log for eacch flow will not be parsed to get 'numSteps'. Defaults to false if left empty.
Values\: true, false
    onlyCompletedFlows - A boolean value. If true, only flows with the 'COMPLETED' state will be returned. If false this filter is ignored. 
Default\: true
a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.46617ae3-a92d-4f06-8847-ec78a4b42c1e.prompt=trustAllRoots a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.5ba2797f-7c46-4fd1-9a7c-0a76279336af.description=
 
Retrieves information about the status of a flow run given its runId. It also returns detailed information about the status of the steps. The flow run information is added as separate results to the operation and the steps status is formated as JSON array where each item contains information about a step status.

Inputs\:
    host - The host running the Central service. The host can also be given as a URL.
Default value\: localhost. 
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Default value\: http.
Valid values\: http, https. 
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default\: 8080.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    runId - The execution id. This may be any started execution (e.g. in progress, paused, completed).
    primaryResultWanted - If true, the operation will return the primary result of the flow run.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false.
    rawResultWanted - If true, the operation will return the raw result of the flow run.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false. 
    duration - Filter the steps by theirs execution time that should be less than duration. The value must be in seconds. If the input is empty it will not filter anything.
Example\: 10
    workersId - Filter the steps by the worker where it was executed. The input is a list delimited by comma (,) with the UUIDs of the workers.
Example\: 085061bf-b6c0-44be-9d79-74f8d5b79891,4cf839fe-c55b-4c12-85dc-abf16290ec0c 
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service. 
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. An SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.  If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, the "trustPassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit 

Results\:
    primaryResult - The primary result. If the flow does not have a result, this is the last step's primary result.    
    returnResult - A message informing the user about the success or failure of the operation.
    status - The status of the flow run. (RUNNING, COMPLETED, SYSTEM_FAILURE, PAUSED, PENDING_PAUSE, CANCELED, PENDING_CANCEL)
    cursorPosition - Represents the current step index in the run history. (e.g. if three steps have been executed, its value is "3")
    runReportUrl - Represents the report link URL to the run.
    runResumeUrl - Represents the resume link URL to run if run is not finished.
    runResponse - Represents the response of the flow run. This is missing if the execution is not complete. (RESOLVED, DIAGNOSED, ERROR, NO_ACTION_TAKEN)
    rawResult - If jsonFormat input is "true", this is a JSON object with the outputs of the flow. If not, it is a string in the format\: {key1\=val1;key2\=val2;key3\=val3}. If rawResultsFromSteps is "true", this map also contains outputs for all the steps (later outputs take precedence).
    stepsStatus - A JSON array representation of the step status. Each item of the array has the following properties\: 
        stepName - The name of the step.
        startTime - Represents the start time of the step since 1/1/1970 00\:00am, in milliseconds.
        endTime - Represents the end time of the step since 1/1/1970 00\:00am, in milliseconds.
        stepResponse - The response of the step, based on the definition of the step.
        flowName -  Represents the name of the flow the step belongs to.
        stepLevel - Zero-based integer that represents the step level in the flow run; each subflow run represents a level. So, if the client runs flowA which runs flowB which in turn runs flowC, the level of all the steps under flowC would be 3. Level zero is the flow itself.
        workerId - The id of the worker where the step was run.

Responses\:
    success -The operation retrieved the status of the running flow.
    failure - Could not connect to Central web service or invalid runId.

Notes\: 
1. Use the operations and flows from Library/Utility Operations/Containers/JSON to parse the "stepsStatus" result.
2. You may add these inputs\:
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the Central host.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the "proxyUsername" input value.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. An SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "keystore" is empty, "keystorePassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    light - If true, a request will be sent to central for the execution summary and the available outputs will be status, runResponse and runReportUrl. If false, requests will be sent to central for both summary and execution log which will be processed in order to obtain all the outputs.
Default value\: false.
Valid values\: true, false.
    jsonFormat - If true array results will be in JSON format, else it will have key\=value pairs separated by semicolon (;).
Default value\: false.
Valid values\: true, false.
    rawResultsFromSteps - If true, all step outputs will be used to populate rawResult.
Default value\: true.
Valid values\: true, false. 
3. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../"your_cert".cer -alias "your_alias" -keystore "OO_Home"/java/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
4. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
    keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
       -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
       -storepass ab987c -validity 180
This creates a certificate chain in a new KeyStore containing only one certificate. It is useful in SSL client authentication because the KeyManager ignores any certificates not included in a certificate chain.
5. If the value assigned to the "trustAllRoots" input is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
6. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled "Advanced Features". Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\="web_server_name",CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the Properties window and press the "Attribute Editor" tab. Check the values of the "servicePrincipalName" attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, http\://"web_server_FQDN"\:port.
7. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.
a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.5dabdd90-670f-49f0-9a70-825d4f0047f5.prompt=trustAllRoots a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.989b2850-8d5b-4693-8f3b-b06231f33d3e.description=
 Returns a paginated list of executed steps, with optional filtering. If a step was executed more than once, this will be reflected in the result. The result includes “virtual steps” such as lanes. The returned objects are “step logs” – detailed objects with all available data about the steps.

Inputs\:
    host - The host running the Central service.
Default value\: localhost
    username - The username to use when connecting to the Central service.
    password - The password to use when connecting to the Central service.
    port - The port the Central service is running on.
Default\: 8080
    protocol - The protocol used to communicate to the Central service.
Valid values\: http, https
Default value\: http
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous
    proxyHost - The hostname or IP address of the computer that acts as proxy server.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the  input value.
    trustAllRoots - If true, enables weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "keystore" is empty, "keystorePassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file.  If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, "trustPassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A  value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    executionID - Execution ID whose steps to count.
    pageNum - This value represents the number of the page that is retrieved.
Valid values\: 1 or greater
Default value\: 1
    pageSize - This value represents the number of steps retrieved inside a page.
Valid values\: 1 or greater
Default value\: 50
    order - The order of the returned steps ; asc for ascending or desc for descending. The order is by step path.
Default value\: asc
    path - Get the step with this exact path.
    pathFrom - Get steps whose paths are greater than this path. "Greater" means that if we looked at a collapsible tree representation of the execution, the greater path would show up lower in the tree.
Example\: 0.10.0 is greater than both 0.10 (its parent) and 0.9.99999
    pathUpTo - Get steps whose path is less than this path (also see pathFrom).
    nameContains - Get steps whose names contain this substring.
    types - Get steps of the given types (comma-separated list, no spaces).
Valid values\: operation, subflow, return_step, other ( for special steps like multi instance and parallel lanes )
    startTime - Get steps that started at this exact timestamp. In order to get accurate results for filters provide the values in Unix Epoch timestamp format for this input.
Example\: 1437565444098
    startTimeFrom - Get steps that started after this timestamp. The time can be in GMT format as it is in first example or in Unix Epoch timestamp as it is in last example. 
Example 1\: Wed, 12 Dec 2012 12\:12\:12 GMT
Example 2\: 1437565444098
    startTimeUpTo - Get steps that started before this timestamp. 
    endTime - Get steps that ended at this exact timestamp. In order to get accurate results for filters provide the values in Unix Epoch timestamp format for this input.
    endTimeFrom - Get steps that ended after this timestamp.
    endTimeUpTo - Get steps that ended before this timestamp.
    durationSec - Gets steps with this exact execution time (seconds).
    durationSecFrom - Get steps that took longer to execute than this value (seconds).
    durationSecUpTo - Get steps that took less time to execute than this value (seconds).
    inputsContain - Get steps where any of the inputs contain this substring, in either the input name or its value.
    rawResultsContain - Get operation-type steps, where any of the raw results (the outputs of the plugin action executed by the operation) contain this substring, in either the input name or its value. 
    primaryResultContains - Get steps where the primary result contains this sub-string. 
Note\: Values over 4,000 bytes cannot be searched.
    stepResultsContain - Get steps where any of the step-defined results contain this sub-string, in either the result name or its value. It is also possible to make a search in the form name\=value. 
Note\: Values over 4,000 bytes cannot be searched.
    responseTypes - Get steps having one of the given response types (comma-separated list, no spaces).
Valid values\: resolved, error, diagnosed, no_action_taken, exception. Exception means the step's execution could not be completed.
    transitionContains - Get steps whose outgoing transition messages contain this substring.  The transition message is either the transition’s description, or the transition’s name if no description has been defined.
    roi - Get steps whose outgoing transitions have this exact ROI value.
    roiFrom - Get steps whose outgoing transitions have ROI values greater than this input.
    roiUpTo - Get steps whose outgoing transitions have ROI values less than this input.
    currentFlowContains - Get steps that belong to flows whose names contain this substring. 
    currentFlowIdContains - Get steps that belong to the flow with the given ID (or a sub-string in it).
    stepIdContains - Get steps with the given static step ID (or a sub-string in it). This ID is hard-coded in the parent flow definition. Note that the same step ID may appear in multiple steps of the execution (for example, when the flow employs a loop). To get a specific step in the execution tree, use the path parameter.
    invokedIdsContain - Get steps that invoke (execute) the operation or subflow with the given UUID (or a sub-string in it).
Note\: for steps that run soft copies of operations, the invoked IDs include both the soft copy and its parent operation.
    userContains - Get steps that executed while the given Central username (or a substring in it) was the execution owner.
    workerIdContains - Get operation-type steps that were executed by the given worker UUID (or a substring in it). 
    workerGroupContains - Get operation-type steps that were executed by a worker in the given worker group name (or a sub-string in it).
    mediaType - The type of the response. If "false" the operation result will be a JSON array representing execution steps details. If "true" the operation result will be a string that contains execution steps details as a CSV formated document.
Valid values\: true, false 
Default value\: false
    
Results\:  
    returnResult - This is the primary result. The complete response returned by OO.
    flowName -  The name of the flow for the parent of the first step returned.
    flowId -  The Id of the flow for the parent of the first step returned.
    stepIdList - The list of step Ids in the JSON response.
    stepNameList - The list of step names in the JSON response.
    stepPathList - The list of step paths in the JSON response.
    stepTypeList - The list of step types in the JSON response.
    stepStatusList - The list of step statuses in the JSON response. 
    invokedIdsList - The list that contains the UUIDs of the flows that invoked the current step.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
    1. All filtering parameters are optional.
    2. Only steps that satisfy all of the given criteria will be returned.
    3. Filtering is performed before the pagination. In other words, when filtering, the pagination will give you pages of search results.
    4. Filtering by text is case insensitive.
    5. Range conditions (such as roiFrom and roiUpTo) are exclusive. See the examples below for details. 
    6. The paths of the steps at the top level of the flow are 0.0 for the 1st step, 0.1 for the 2nd and so on. If the 2nd step (0.1) is a subflow, then the paths of the steps in that subflow are 0.1.0, 0.1.1 and so on. 
    7. The "mediaTypes" input works only for platforms (Central) with 10.50 version or higher. For platforms with version lower than 10.50 the input value is ignored.
    8. When platform (Central) version is 10.50 or higher and "mediaTypes" input is set on "true" then the response CSV formated document will contain all the logs of the execution no matter if any filter is set.
    9. Unix Epoch timestamp represents the number of milliseconds that have elapsed since 1 January 1970.

Examples\: 
    1. roi\=7.5&roiFrom\=7.5&roiUpTo\=30        	7.5 ≤ roi < 30
        roiFrom\=7.5&roiUpTo\=30	7.5 < roi < 30
        roi\=7.5&roiFrom\=7.5		roi ≥ 7.5
        roiFrom\=7.5		roi > 7.5
        roi\=7.5			roi \= 7.5
        roiUpTo\=7.5&roiFrom\=7.5	roi ≠ 7.5
        roiUpTo\=7.5&roiFrom\=30	roi < 7.5  or  roi > 30
    
    It is not possible to make a search in the form  x ≤ roi ≤ y  (i.e. with ≤ on both sides).
a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.b479a2d6-9cac-4c82-9dcc-8c5e4b9d8367.prompt=runId a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.bd3963a9-8354-4b77-9c9a-afeda65fb6d5.prompt=protocol a3963064-bcf0-4590-a28c-18c15ffd759a.fcda9a4a-39b2-41eb-83c6-faf19466ce52.prompt=protocol
flow.name: Get Run Log
